Name: Maya M
Additional Advice?: This website helped me so much. Thank you. I told myself if I won, I would upload here ! Thank you.

Name: Martin Torres
Additional Advice?: Start early, have a lot of people give feedback, and make sure it's your voice that carries through at the end. Make your story compelling!

Name: Darren Boydston
Additional Advice?: Get as many people in your field as you can to look over your drafts!

Name: Katy Felkner
Additional Advice?: BUG YOUR RECOMMENDERS EARLY AND OFTEN. I had to withdraw my submission in my first year of grad school because a letter writer missed the deadline. I reminded him a day before, but I didn't check the status on the due date, and he was a few minutes late because he thought the deadline was in local time not EST. Remind your reviewers as much as they need and be careful with timezones!

Name: Roberto Peralta
Additional Advice?: My CV at time of application: https://drive.google.com/file/d/1-_JLZI5uN_9zRvI_1AhuXdAn7da9XaF9/view?usp=sharing  Have people from many professions (STEM and non-STEM)/ages/experiences read your material.

Name: Anonymous
Additional Advice?: Be very explicit in outlining how your experiences fit the NSF profile. Reviewers skim these applications quickly so it's important to be straightforward and clear.

Name: Katya Leidig
Area: Physics and Astronomy - Astronomy and Astrophysics

Name: Emily Isko
Additional Advice?: Have as many people as possible read your essays and give feedback. The more editing and drafts, the better.

Name: Molly Griston
Area: STEM Education and Learning Research — Science Education

Name: Angelo Hawa
Additional Advice?: Start early and stay in touch with professors along the way! Literature reviews are a good source to help with the research proposal.

Name: Ian Marrs
Additional Advice?: Remember that the reviewers are people too. Science as an industry can seem cold and unfeeling, but it is run by people with biases and emotions who will respond to your honesty and unique life story. Also, start work early and, if your advisor is willing, communicate with your advisor often to ensure you're on the right track.

Name: Ravyn Malatesta
Area: Chemistry - Chemical Structure, Dynamics, and Mechanism

Name: Sebastian Vargas
Additional Advice?: Get your essays reviewed by as many people as possible, tell your story with a punch.

Name: Isabel Kain
Additional Advice?: Start early, iterate often, and seek feedback from lots of different people (even if you feel like you're being needy). I talked to two subfield experts, two scientists in different fields altogether, and three non-scientists, and their collective feedback helped immeasurably, and all in different ways.

Name: Kyle Korman
Additional Advice?: Explain any dip in undergrad GPA. Explanation goes a long way since GPA is a large factor.

Name: James Skripchuk
Area: STEM Education and Learning Research - Technology Education
Additional Advice?: Don't be afraid to write down stuff about you that may seem silly/cringe. Embrace your uniqueness.

Name: Jennifer Le
Area: Life Sciences - Systems and Molecular Biology

Name: Anonymous
Additional Advice?: "The Professor Is In" - a great book for anyone looking at tenure track. The foolproof grant template helped me draft out ideas for NSF. https://theprofessorisin.com/2011/07/05/dr-karens-foolproof-grant-template/

Name: Julia (Jules) Fowler
Area: Physics and Astronomy - Astronomy and Astrophysics
Additional Advice?: Tie every awesome skill you want to showcase to some cool and impactful result for a wider community.

Name: Anonymous
Additional Advice?: Add in a visual diagram to illustrate a conceptual framework for your study (if applicable)

Name: Anonymous
Area: Chemistry - Chemical Theory, Models and Computational Methods

Name: Grace Deitzler
Additional Advice?: Revise, revise, and revise again, and get as many people as possible to read your statements.

Name: Juan Sebastian Rubio
Additional Advice?: Highlight key sentences to aid the reader, especially those that won't have time to read the entire research proposal/SOP in detail.

Name: Ava Vargason
Additional Advice?: Focus on *your* contributions to science, discuss interesting/innovative future plans for outreach if you're lacking in broader impacts

Name: Madison McMinn
Additional Advice?: Feel free to contact me - I wrote this application 100% by myself with only this website to guide me so I'm happy to help anyone that comes from a small university where no one has ever applied before and needs help.

Name: Holly Kundel
Additional Advice?: Write as many drafts as you can and get feedback from multiple people. Also, make sure to really explain your broader impacts in your personal statement. For the research proposal, don't worry so much about the cost of your experiment or the overall feasibility, just show that you can think like a scientist.
